Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot of water with a large pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil. Mince or grate the @garlic{4%cloves}. Halve, peel, and mince the @shallot{2%units}. Finely chop the @parsley{1/2%ounce}. Zest and halve the @lemon{2%units}. Core, seed, and thinly slice the @red bell pepper{2%units}.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%teaspoon} in a large #pan over medium-high heat. Add the bell peppers to the pan and cook, tossing for ~{6-7%minutes}, until slightly caramelized. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Cook the linguine: Add the @linguine{12%ounce} to the boiling water and cook for ~{9-11%minutes}, until al dente. Drain, reserving 1/4 cup pasta water.

Meanwhile, heat another large drizzle of olive oil in the same pan over medium heat. Add the shallot, garlic, and as many @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} as you like to the pan. Cook, tossing for ~{2-3%minutes}, until softened. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add the @shrimp{20%ounce} to the pan and cook, tossing, for another ~{2-3%minutes}, until opaque. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the drained linguine to the pan along with the red bell pepper, reserved pasta water, lemon zest, a squeeze of lemon juice, and @butter{2%tablespoon}. Toss over medium heat for ~{1-2%minutes}, until fully combined and heated through. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Plate: Serve the lemony shrimp linguine sprinkled with parsley and chili flakes, if desired. Enjoy!

> Lemon, butter, and shrimp is one of our all-time favorite combinations. Amped up by garlic and spicy chili flakes, this is a dish made great by its simplicity. The addition of caramelized bell pepper adds a nice touch of sweetness. If your kids don't like spicy, simply add the chili flakes to the adult plates at the end!

> Nutrition per serving: 630 kcal, 15g fat (5g saturated), 79g carbohydrates, 10g sugar, 48g protein, 8g fiber, 415mg sodium.